Prefectural Fishery Federation "Start discussion toward full-scale operation" Chairman Nozaki "Iwaki Minpo Official Website"
Following TEPCO's Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant accident, discussions for full-scale operation of test operations off the coast of Fukushima Prefecture were made in each district.
Mr. Tetsu Nozaki, President of the Federation of Fisheries Cooperatives of the prefecture, said, "As the Federation of Fisheries Cooperatives of the prefecture, we believe that a flow toward full-scale operation is necessary, and I want the representatives to gather and start discussions."
The Union Presidents' Association also approved the formal addition of cassago, sakura trout, and murasoi off the coast of Fukushima Prefecture to the target species for test operations.
The remaining two species of fish are binosgai and commoncasbe.
At the end of the meeting, President Nozaki responded to the press and stressed that the start of full-scale operations has not been decided.
Regarding the treated water after purifying contaminated water at the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant, Mr. Yoshiaki Harada, former Minister of the Environment and Ichiro Matsui, Mayor of Osaka City, said, "The Keren-like argument is a problem, and the position against the release of the ocean remains unchanged."
When discussing full-scale operations, Akira EGAWA, head of Iwaki City Fisheries Cooperative, pointed out that "it is necessary to suck up opinions from the bottom," and said that he respects the intentions of the members.
A board meeting was held at the subsidiary branch offices, and after solving the problems one by one, it concluded as a city fishing cooperative.
Kanji Tachiya, head of the Soma Futaba Fisheries Cooperative, said, "In addition to the fishermen, it is necessary to discuss it with the buyers."
The Soma Futaba Fisheries Cooperative is supported by the government and seven new ships will enter next year.
