"Korea wants to return to GSOMIA" Assistant Secretary of State (Sankei Shimbun) - Yahoo!
U.S. Under Secretary of State for South Korea and Japan, Napper, in an interview with the Sankei Shimbun at the residence of the U.S. Ambassador in Tokyo, said on November 27 that "Korea hopes to reconsider and come back to the decision to destroy the military information comprehensive protection agreement (GSOMIA) between Japan and Korea that expires on November 23."
It is unusual for a senior U.S. official to mention a reconsideration of GSOMIA's destruction.
GSOMIA is based on the agreement between Japan, South Korea, the United States, the United States, and South Korea to share missile launch information.
In August, Korea announced that it would destroy the agreement with Japan, and if it expires, the framework for protecting military information will collapse.
"Without GSOMIA, we cannot effectively respond to the crisis," said Napper.
He strongly urged the return of Korea, saying, "There is time until revocation."
He also pointed out that the joint flight training conducted by China and Russia in July over the Sea of Japan was "the first in history" and stressed that "it is essential that the United States, Korea and Japan, which share values such as democracy and human rights, collaborate in alliance relations."
He pointed out that the recent deterioration in Japan-Korea relations "damages the national interests of the United States."
"There is no intention of mediation," he said, "Japan and Korea will play a positive role to fill the gap."
(Yusuke HIRATA)
Tokaimura criticality accident, 20 years in 30 days 300 nuclear facility troubles: Hokkaido Shimbun
According to an interview with the Nuclear Regulation Authority (NRA), 336 cases of accidents and failures at nuclear facilities across Japan were reported between 2000 and 2006 following the critical accident in Tokai-mura, Ibaraki Prefecture, which was the first in the history of nuclear power in Japan.
It has been 30 days and 20 years since the critical accident that alarmed the safety myth of the nuclear industry.
In the report, although the International Assessment Scale (INES), which shows seriousness, accounted for about 90% of the cases (not important for safety) and those that were not evaluated, it is necessary to continuously raise safety awareness based on lessons learned from the accident and the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant accident of TEPCO in 2011.
Koichi Soda, who has completed the story and original drawings of creative picture books, is soliciting donations for publication.
Koichi Soda (64), an artist from the Echizen City Regional Development Cooperation Volunteer in Fukui Prefecture, started a crowdfunding campaign aimed at publishing creative picture books inspired by legends in Fukui Prefecture in order to promote town development using picture books.
Mr. Soda, who was originally from Hokkaido and started his activities as a member of the cooperative group in April this year, says, "I want to convey the heart of the kindness of Fukui people based on deep faith through picture books."
[Donation is here] To convey Fukui's heart.
While Mr. Soda is active as an artist working on contemporary art based on mathematics, he has also been active as a co-operative since the end of the calendar.
After working on the town development of Nagano, Kumamoto and Tochigi, he joined Echizen City in April this year.
The city, which produced Riko Kako and Chihiro Iwasaki, aims to create a town using picture books.
Mr. Soda lived in the city and said, "I was surprised by the depth of compassion that I could understand for the first time."
What attracted attention was the legend of the city of Awara, 'The face of the demon of the bride'.
In contrast to the mother-in-law who couldn't take off the demon's face, the gentle-hearted bride-in-law continues to chant Nenbutsu (Buddhist invocation) to help her mother-in-law without worrying about being surprised by her face.
"I forgot my hatred, returned with kindness and kindness, and felt the origin of the faith and kindness of the people of Fukui."
Inspired by the original picture book, Soda went to Yoshizaki Gobo in Awara City as soon as he arrived to complete the story "Meoto Oni" where a couple and a boy of gentle demons appear.
From June, he drew 10 scenes with warm watercolors, taking advantage of his job, and the materials of picture books were mixed.
In addition, the cover of picture books will be made with washi using Echizen washi, a traditional craft that lives in Echizen City.
This is a chance for parents and children to enjoy the touch of Japanese paper by reading and listening.
The goal of the donation amount is 850,000 yen for 600 copies.
The deadline is October 25.
Mr. Soda said, "Fukui's heart, which has been nurtured under the historical Buddhist culture, is proud throughout Japan.
I want to tell children what true kindness and compassion are handed down through picture books."
It is one of the projects that Fukui Prefecture certifies 11 projects for regional revitalization that are challenged by the cooperation team and business operators in the prefecture, and supports using hometown tax.
The Fukui Shimbun publishes information and the Fukui Bank cooperates with management support.
Donations can be made from the crowdfunding website Lady For.
