Sakura shrimp in the growth process PT in Shizuoka City, etc. | Shizuoka Shimbun at Es
Sakura shrimp born this year was successfully photographed in the deep sea of Suruga Bay on the 11th off Kamahara, Shimizu Ward, Shizuoka City (provided by Yui Sakura shrimp project)
The Yui Sakura Ebi Project, a consortium of marine industry clusters led by industry, academia, and government officials in Shizuoka City, has succeeded in photographing sakura shrimp, which is thought to have been born during the spawning season this spring and summer, at a depth of 290 meters in Suruga Bay.
The video of the growth process is valuable, and people concerned want to lead to the elucidation of the ecology of sakura shrimp, which has many mysteries.
The photograph was taken near the bottom of the sea about 1 to 5 km off the coast of the Kamahara area, Shimizu Ward, the city.
A total of 300 were confirmed in 17 minutes.
In the daytime, the conventional knowledge that sakura shrimp in the deep sea form a certain group at the bottom of the sea was reaffirmed.
The adult body is about 40 mm long, and the individual reflected is about 23 mm long.
The spawning period was identified by matching the seasonal data of the caught shrimp.
Detailed analysis is requested by Fujitsu Software Technologies and Shizuoka Technical College, which comprise the team.
Keisuke Mizuno, Project Leader, said, "I want to capture the living figure of individuals in the growth process, including fry."
Mother Ranch Reopens, Chiba Prefecture People Free Damaged by Typhoon until the end of October | Shizuoka Shimbun at es
Chiba-kun, the mascot character of Chiba Prefecture, welcomes visitors at the Mother Ranch, which has reopened its business.
Mother Ranch in Futsu City, Chiba Prefecture, which had been closed since September 9 due to power outages and damage to facilities caused by Typhoon No. 15, resumed operations on August 28.
Residents in Chiba Prefecture are free to enter the affected areas by the end of October.
Under the clear autumn weather, many people visited the park at the same time as the opening, and at the entrance gate, the mascot character of the prefecture "Chiba-kun" who ran to support was welcomed.
The roof was covered with blue sheets and some facilities continued to be repaired, but half of the restaurants started to reopen.
Kenji Mitani (34), a family member of Sagamihara City, said with a smile, "I was worried about when I would resume.I came to enjoy the event of potato digging, thinking that it would lead to reconstruction."
