today's caddy's best shot.
1 W shot is not necessarily a tie-up.
There is also the so-called "naodora" technique in which you hit a ball on the ground when you want to make a distance with a second hit of par 5 etc.
In recent years, 1W has the risk of scattering balls due to its large head volume, but there are players who practice this frequently on the ground.
It is Kansei Ikemura who is waiting for the first victory of the tour.
In his seventh year as a professional, 24 years old is 166 cm tall and small, but he is currently seventh in the driving distance category (average 304.02yd).
While he excelled at long shots, one of the challenges was the accuracy of Fairwaywood.
In early spring, he opened his eyes saying, "Because the shot of the spoon (3W) was bad, I wanted to try Naodora."
From the practice round, the ball is dropped on the grass of Tielia, and occasionally swings 1W.
In the case where big carry is required, the tip is often used, but both sides make effective use of Naodora in narrow halls.
"It can be used in a hall where the eye line is lowered."
