Mr. Onsarigo helped Nagai and elementary school students work as pacemakers on land, and three people updated the tournament record | Yamagata Shimbun
Children run at 800 meters.
On the left is Joseph Onsarigo, a pacemaker in Nagai City, Japan.
A goodwill track competition for Nagai City Elementary School was held on the 26th at the Koyo Seiki Athlete Field Nagai (city track and field stadium) in Nagai, and Joseph Onsarigo (27), a long-distance runner belonging to Nasu Construction (city), served as a pacemaker in some races.
With a light run, three new records of the tournament were set up.
Onsarigo pulled the children in a total of four races, 1000 meters for men and 800 meters for women.
Chiya Koseki (Hirano Ko 6) was ranked first in the men's competition in 3 minutes and 4.38, and Ransei Shigara (Isazawa Ko 6) was ranked first in the women's competition in 2 minutes and 34.17.
Mr. Koseki said, "It was hard to keep up with fast Onsarigo players, but I was able to endure them."
Onsarigo was delighted that "the children were good at running, and I had a perfect job."
The competition was organized by the Nagai City Elementary School Sports Promotion Association to promote friendship among sixth graders in the city.
