Okayama Art Exchange Opens in the City Center: Sanyo Shimbun Digital | San'Digi
People around the classroom that depicts the future 3,000 years later
The international art exhibition "Okayama Art Exchange 2019" held every three years in central Okayama City (hosted by the executive committee of the city, prefecture, etc.) opened on the 27th.
Along with the mysterious title "IF THE SNAKE If Snake," 18 artists from 9 countries enjoy cutting-edge art.
This is the second time since 16 years, and we have invited the French artist Pierre Yuig as artistic director.
Approximately 40 films and three-dimensional works will be shown at 13 locations including the former Uchiyamashita Ko (Marunouchi, Kita Ward, Okayama City) and the prefectural Tenjinyama Culture Plaza (Tenjin-cho).
Prior to the opening ceremony, a small opening ceremony was held, and about 100 people attended.
Mayor Masao Omori and General Producer Yasuharu Ishikawa, the chairman of the executive committee, said, "A work that stimulates intellectual sensibility and stimulates imagination and creativity, and it becomes an exhibition that attracts attention from the world."
Families and children studying outside the school visited the school immediately and found a snake-shaped robot that responds to the sounds of the surrounding area in the dohyo of the schoolyard.
I enjoyed the art that led to different worlds.
While traveling with my father, a first-year high school student in Tokyo (15) said, "It's interesting to see the work that makes use of the atmosphere of the old school building, and I can imagine the time that flowed into this place."
It is closed on Mondays (in case of national holidays) until 24 November.
Hong Kong, rally in the 5th year of the Umbrella Movement tens of thousands, aim for ordinary elections | Shizuoka Shimbun at Es
Five years have passed since the launch of the Umbrella Movement, and the people who gathered at the meeting venue: Hong Kong (joint)
[Collaboration with Hong Kong] On the 28th of May, 2014, a large-scale demonstration called the "Ambrella Movement" was launched to democratize the election of Hong Kong's Chief Administrative Officer.
Some young people occupied the main road around the venue and threw fire bottles into the government building.
As protests started with the amendment of the Fugitive Ordinance continued, the participants renewed their determination to fight until the realization of a "true ordinary election" that could not be won at the time.
The protests, which took full swing in June, reached 112 days, more than 79 days after the Umbrella Movement, and the demands of the demonstrators expanded to "five major demands" such as electoral reform.
